      {
        "id": 2540722,
        "name": "Rick Allen",
        "username": "Rick_Allen",
        "avatar_template": "/user_avatar/www.wineberserkers.com/rick_allen/{size}/90255_2.png",
        "created_at": "2018-12-15T05:05:10.000Z",
        "cooked": "<aside class=\"quote no-group\" data-post=\"6\" data-topic=\"147995\">\n<blockquote>\n<p>Does anyone know the difference between 1er La Boudriette Rouge and 1er Clos de la Boudriette Rouge?</p>\n</blockquote>\n</aside>\n<p>I don\u2019t know the answer, but I have a theory.  La Boudriotte is somewhat of a catch-all climate.  There are six climates that can use the name: La Boudriotte, Les Fairendes, Les Petite Fairendes, La Roquemaure, Champ Jendreau, and Les Chaumes.  BTW, all these climates along with, by my count, 17(!) others can also use the climate of Morgeot.  I suspect that the La Boudriotte comes from some mix of the six eligible climates while the Clos de la Boudriotte may come from only the La Boudriotte climate, or some portion of it.</p>",
        "post_number": 7,
        "post_type": 1,
        "posts_count": 7,
